<CaseStudyLayout title="End-to-End Capex Sourcing & Category Management for an Indian E&P Operator">
  <h1>End-to-End Capex Sourcing & Category Management for an Indian E&P Operator</h1>

  <div class="cs-spec">
    <div><p class="k">Functional Topic</p><p class="v">Capex Sourcing, Category Management & Supplier Strategy</p></div>
    <div><p class="k">Industry</p><p class="v">Oil & Gas — Upstream (E&P)</p></div>
    <div><p class="k">Role</p><p class="v">Capex Category & Sourcing Lead (Accenture)</p></div>
    <div><p class="k">Duration</p><p class="v">12 Months</p></div>
  </div>

  <h2>The Challenge</h2>
  <p>An Indian exploration & production (E&P) operator was running a large upstream capital programme, but sourcing was happening project by project. Each package — EPC, surface facilities, drilling & completions — was tendered in isolation, with no category strategy, no aggregated demand view, and limited leverage with a concentrated supplier base. The operator needed to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Move from fragmented, project-led buying to a coordinated capex category strategy.</li>
    <li>Build supplier leverage in categories where a handful of contractors dominated.</li>
    <li>Run disciplined end-to-end sourcing — from category strategy through to award and contract.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>My Role</h2>
  <p>As part of Accenture's engagement team, I led capex sourcing and category management across the major spend categories — building category strategies for EPC, surface facilities, and drilling & completions; aggregating demand across projects; running sourcing end to end (qualification, RFx, evaluation, negotiation, award); and embedding category governance and supplier-management discipline in-house.</p>

  <h2>The Approach</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Segment the capex spend</strong> — broke the programme into managed categories and sized each.</li>
    <li><strong>Build category strategies</strong> — set a differentiated approach per category based on supply-market structure.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggregate demand</strong> — consolidated requirements across projects to build leverage and avoid duplicated tendering.</li>
    <li><strong>Run sourcing end to end</strong> — qualification → RFx → evaluation → negotiation → award.</li>
    <li><strong>Embed governance</strong> — left category playbooks, supplier-management routines, and in-house capability.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Sourcing Strategy by Category</h2>
  <div class="cs-cards">
    <div><p class="m">EPC 48%</p><h4>Structured competition</h4><p>The largest category earned the most disciplined competitive process — a wide qualified field narrowed through formal stage-gates to award.</p></div>
    <div><p class="m">Surface 30%</p><h4>Package & frame agreements</h4><p>Recurring requirements were consolidated into frame agreements, avoiding repeated full tenders and building continuity with capable suppliers.</p></div>
    <div><p class="m">D&C 22%</p><h4>Rate & availability management</h4><p>In a constrained rig and services market, the focus shifted to securing rates and availability rather than maximising the bidder count.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h2>Results</h2>
  <ul class="result-list">
    <li><strong>Category strategies established</strong> across EPC, surface facilities, and drilling & completions — replacing project-by-project buying.</li>
    <li><strong>Demand aggregated</strong> across projects to build leverage with a concentrated supplier base.</li>
    <li><strong>End-to-end sourcing run</strong> from qualification through to award on the major capital packages.</li>
    <li><strong>Governance and capability embedded</strong> — category playbooks and supplier-management routines left in-house.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="cs-closing">
    <p>A capital programme sourced project by project leaks leverage at every award. Managing capex as categories — aggregating demand, matching each category's sourcing approach to its supply market, and governing it as a programme — is what converts scattered tenders into durable commercial advantage.</p>
  </div>

  <p class="cs-note"><strong>Illustrative & partly anonymized.</strong> Accenture is named as the engagement context; the E&P client is withheld. Category splits and the sourcing funnel are directional, built to demonstrate the approach rather than report exact programme figures.</p>
</CaseStudyLayout>
